      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's a good start. my students are also asking about the criticisms of this idea though. some people say that 'substantive due process' is basically just a way for judges to make up new laws instead of following what's actually written in the Constitution. how would you address that perspective in the lesson?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics of substantive due process argue that it's a form of judicial activism, where judges impose their own values and policies on the Constitution, rather than strictly adhering to its text. They claim that this approach undermines the rule of law and the checks and balances system, allowing judges to overstep their authority and impose their own will on the country. However, proponents of substantive due process argue that it's a necessary tool for adapting the Constitution to changing societal values and protecting fundamental rights that aren't explicitly listed in the document.",
      "source": "target",
